gate, Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1340–1396":"1340–1396","1322–1384":"1322–1384","1365–1394":"1365–1394","1350–1396":"1350–1396","1364–1438":"1364–1438","1280–1388":"1280–1388","1290–1380":"1290–1380","1363":"1363","1396":"1396","1340":"1340","1384":"1384","1350":"1350","1394":"1394","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","4 September 1394":"4 September 1394","1378":"1378","1388":"1388","1322":"1322","1365":"1365","1364":"1364","March 1384":"March 1384","1438":"1438","Grafton, Yorkshire, England":"Grafton, Yorkshire, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Somerset, or Worcester, City of Worcester, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","Bedlisgate, Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":42,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas John Bedlisgate was born in 1340, in Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Bedlisgate, was 60 and his mother, Joan de FitzWith, was 50. He married Joan Beauchamp in 1363, in Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1396, in Grafton, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 56."},"et":{"1340–1396":"1340–1396","1322–1384":"1322–1384","1365–1394":"1365–1394","1350–1396":"1350–1396","1364–1438":"1364–1438","1280–1388":"1280–1388","1290–1380":"1290–1380","1363":"1363","1396":